📘 DAY 16 — Caching, Redis & Performance Optimization
1️⃣ Why Caching Exists (Core Theory)

Database calls are expensive:

API → Service → DB → Response


Each DB query involves:

Network I/O

Disk reads

Query parsing

Locks & transactions

Caching stores frequently accessed data in memory:

API → Cache (Redis) → Response


👉 Memory access is 100–1000x faster than DB.

2️⃣ Types of Caching (Interview Favorite)
✅ Application Cache

Inside application memory.

Example:

Caffeine

ConcurrentHashMap

✔ Fast
❌ Lost on restart

✅ Distributed Cache (Most Used in Finance)

Example:

Redis

Hazelcast

✔ Shared across services
✔ Survives restarts
✔ Scalable

Goldman Sachs heavily uses distributed caching patterns.

3️⃣ Spring Cache Abstraction

Spring provides annotation-based caching.

Core Annotations
✅ @Cacheable

Stores result if not present.

@Cacheable("accounts")
public Account getAccount(Long id)


Flow:

Check Cache
   ↓
Miss → Call DB → Store → Return
Hit  → Return directly

✅ @CachePut

Always executes method and updates cache.

@CachePut(value="accounts", key="#account.id")


Used after updates.

✅ @CacheEvict

Removes stale cache.

@CacheEvict(value="accounts", key="#id")


Used after delete/update.

4️⃣ Cache Key Concept (VERY IMPORTANT)

Cache works like:

key → value


Example:

accounts::1 → Account JSON


Bad key design causes:

wrong data

cache collision

stale responses

Best practice:

key = "#accountId"

5️⃣ Cache TTL (Time To Live)

Financial systems cannot keep data forever.

Example:

.entryTtl(Duration.ofMinutes(10))


Why TTL?

Market data changes

Account balances update

Prevent stale reads

6️⃣ Cache Aside Pattern (GS Favorite)

Most common architecture:

1. Check cache
2. If miss → DB
3. Store in cache
4. Return


Spring @Cacheable implements this automatically.

7️⃣ Why NOT Cache JPA Entities

Interview GOLD question.

Problems:

Hibernate lazy proxies

Serialization failures

Large object graphs

Session leakage

✅ Solution:

Entity → DTO → Cache

8️⃣ Serialization in Redis

Redis stores bytes, not Java objects.

Serialization options:

Serializer	Used?	Reason
JDK	❌	brittle
String	❌	limited
JSON	✅	readable & safe

Best practice:

GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer

9️⃣ Cache Problems (Real Production)
Cache Stampede

Many requests hit DB when cache expires simultaneously.

Solution:

stagger TTL

locking

prewarming

Cache Penetration

Requests for non-existing data repeatedly hit DB.

Solution:

cache null briefly.

Cache Invalidation (Hardest Problem)

When DB updates:

DB updated ❌ cache still old


Fix:

@CacheEvict after update

⭐ Goldman Sachs Interview Questions (Day 16)
🔥 Q1 (Very Common)

What is caching and why is Redis used?

✅ Answer:

Caching stores frequently accessed data in memory to reduce database load and latency. Redis is used because it is an in-memory distributed datastore supporting high throughput and low latency, suitable for high-frequency systems.

🔥 Q2

Difference between @Cacheable and @CachePut?

Annotation	Behavior
Cacheable	Skips execution if cached
CachePut	Always executes and updates cache
🔥 Q3

Why shouldn’t we cache JPA entities?

Expected answer:

JPA entities contain lazy-loaded proxies and persistence context references which may fail serialization and cause stale or inconsistent cache states. DTO caching is safer.

🔥 Q4

What happens when cache expires under heavy load?

Answer:

Cache stampede occurs where many requests hit DB simultaneously. Solutions include locking, request coalescing, or staggered TTL.

🔥 Q5 (Advanced GS Question)

How do you maintain cache consistency?

Answer:

Write-through or cache-aside strategy

Evict/update cache after DB modification

Event-driven invalidation (Kafka)

🔥 Q6 (Scenario Based)

Account balance updated but API returns old value. Why?

Expected reasoning:

Cache not evicted

TTL too long

Multiple cache nodes out of sync

